%\subsection{Corner Slope Diffraction for Conducting Tip and Imperfectly Conducting Corner and Tip}
%Based on the corner slope diffraction detailed in chapter \ref{Ch:CSD_and_H_Plane_Horn_Pattern}, slope diffraction from the perfectly conducting tip\index{Conducting tip} can be evaluated. Also corner slope diffraction for the perfectly conducting case can be extended for imperfectly conducting corner and tip\index{Imperfectly!conducting corner}\index{Imperfectly!conducting tip}.
\begin{enumerate}[(i)]
\item \textbf{Corner diffraction field associated with one corner at the intersection of three edges of a perfectly conducting three dimensional wedge:}\\
The H-plane pattern computed in Chapter \ref{Ch:GTD_H_Plane_Horn_Pattern} used the corner diffracted field obtained on the basis of the available heuristic corner diffraction coefficient for a corner formed at the end of a plate by a pair of finite straight edges. However, it can be seen that the horn corner is actually at the intersection of three edges of a finite perfectly conducting wedge. Further studies should therefore be made to obtain a solution for the latter problem.

\item \textbf{Corner slope diffraction field associated with one corner at the intersection of three edges of a perfectly conducting three dimensional wedge:}\\
The H-plane pattern computed in Chapter \ref{Ch:CSD_and_H_Plane_Horn_Pattern} used the corner slope diffracted field obtained on the basis of corner slope diffraction coefficient of (\ref{c_s_cxf}) for a corner formed at the end of a plate by a pair of finite straight edges. However, it can be seen that the horn corner is actually at the intersection of three edges of a finite perfectly conducting wedge. Further studies should therefore be made to obtain a solution to the latter problem.





\item \textbf{A more analytical (versus heuristic) corner diffraction coefficient could be used:}\\
Marhefka and Brinkley \cite{Marhefka_Far_Zone_Scattering_Flat_Plate_Cube} obtained a UTD corner effect from the integration of the physical optics (PO) and fringe components of Michaeli\rq s edge. This corner diffraction coefficient could be used instead of \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction}, \cite{Sikta_F_corner_diffraction} in the computations to determine improvements, if any, in the horn  radiation and Sikta\rq s triangle scatter predictions. Further, based on \cite{Ivrissimtzis_uniform_ray_higher_order_terms} a higher order corner diffraction could be used to see if further improvements, if any, in horn radiation pattern predictions are obtained. 


\item \textbf{The need for a finite-edge edge diffraction coefficient:}\\
The GTD scattered field for Sikta\rq s triangle shows steep rise for angles at and around $\theta_g=90^\circ$. The UTD (version of GTD) edge diffraction coefficient of the corresponding the canonical half-plane problem was used in this case. Though in this case of at and near the reflection boundary, the UTD result is finite, the scattered field magnitude is high. The half-plane problem is not necessarily the suitable canonical problem for all cases of edge diffraction \cite{Sanyal_Bhatt_curved_plate}. It is clear that at these angles the  edge diffraction coefficient needs refinement to incorporate suitable higher order diffraction mechanism. 

\item \textbf{Performance analysis of horn antenna as EMFS using finite edge GTD technique:}\\
The GTD on axis gain formula of pyramidal horn antenna (\ref{gtd_Gain_1})(6.42) given in \cite{Jull_gain_pyramidal_horns} is based on two-dimensional E-plane sectoral horn analysis. Further GTD analysis of horn as EMFS should be carried using on axis pyramidal horn antenna gain formula obtained through finite edge GTD analysis of three-dimensional pyramidal horn.
\end{enumerate}


